                            <br />
                            <p>While the lore and ways of pre-Christian Scandanavia may have been obfuscated by the passage of time, the myths and legends that remain to us still captivate audiences and color our fantasy worlds.  While it isn't possible to achieve "historical accuracy" in most Viking themed games, Stromgard takes an approach that's more focused on the "feeling" of believability.  Stromgard's monster, legends, gods, and figures were all inspired by real surviving documents- mostly the Poetic and Prose Eddas (arguably the most well-known collections of Norse myth) but also Beowulf, the Icelandic Sagas, and a few more modern Northern European and Celtic tales.</p>
                            <img style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 5px; float: right; height:372px; width:301px;" src="~/Content/img/Stromgard/beowulf.jpeg" class="img-fluid" />
                            <p>Stromgard includes a chapter on historical sources and addresses some of the more prevalant facts and myths about Vikings and pagan Norse peoples.  This adds robust framework that GMs and players can utilize in creating characters, pulling from period-typical narrative impetus, or simply roleplaying in a believable society (even if fantasy is an accepted element).  The oldest written sources of Norse lore, The Eddas, weren't penned until hundreds of years after their stories had supposedly taken place, which unfortunately adds some more contemporary bias.</p>
                            <p>While real historical accuracy is impossible and choosing a hard date somewhere on the timeline of the Viking Age isn't necessary in Stromgard, having the extra context and research already prepared helps inform decisions and support an intricate, dynamic setting.</p>
                            <br />
