                            <h2>The Setting</h2>
                            <br />
                            <p>The realm of Stromgard is huge and contains a great amount of detail that GMs and players can alter, customize, or influence on the fly.  One of <a href="https://dungeon-world.com/">Dungeon World's</a> guiding principles is <strong>draw maps, leave blanks</strong> and Stromgard was designed to do exactly that- provide players with guidance and structure to support a believable world and an epic narrative but there is always room for players to add or remove anything they wish without having to wrangle suddenly-nonfunctioning narrative threads. Here's the kind of information the book provides:</p>
                            <img style="padding: 10px 20px 5px 5px; float: left;" src="~/Content/img/Stromgard/mapsite.png" class="img-fluid" />
                            <h3>Society</h3>
                            <p>The Wyrd of Stromgard seeks to provide a basic overview of what society is like as a backdrop for the rest of the game- <em>heaviliy</em> inspired by historic accounts, Stromgard lays out world that is detailed and engaging.  With information on economy, power structures, culture, and language players will have plenty of narrative hooks and intriging details to work with right out of the gate.</p>
                            <h3>Races</h3>
                            <p>Stromgard is also home to several prominent races and a chapter has been dedicated to each of the most populous peoples in the realm- mortal and immortal elves, dvergar and mortal dwarves, gnomes, halflings, humans, and Jotnar (or Ice Giants, as they are sometimes referred to).  Each chapter explores their unique histories and creation myths, sub-populations, political relationships, physcial appearances, and cultures.</p>
                            <h3>Warfare</h3>
                            <p>Vikings were most famous for their conquest through Europe and their push to ransack the land and The Wyrd of Stromgard provides setting knowledge to help GMs recreate this turbulent and dangerous period with minimal effort.  A chapter on warfare covers common tactics, motiviations, naval capabilities, and cultural influences that take from the tales of historic Viking raids. </p>
                            <h3>Gods and the Nine Realms</h3>
                            <p>The world tree and it's nine realms are possibly one of the most iconic features of Norse myth and it has been incorporated into Stromgard in an easy-to-digest fashion without having expected players or GMs to read many old manuscripts.  Each of Yggdrasil's nine realms is explored succinctly but in detail, along with the gods that preside over them, their rank in the divine hierarchy, and their sphere of influence.</p>
                            <h3>Places</h3>
                            <p>A map and list of premade steadings is ready for GMs to utilize whenever they need and include tags, detailed descriptions, and locations.</p>
                            <h3>The Arcane</h3>
                            <p>Magic's sway over Stromgard is discussed in a chapter of its own, including entries on Seeing and Wyrd-magic- perhaps not unique to Norse lore but certainly one of the most aesthetically iconic facets of it.</p>
